It says the pandemic, coupled with locust swarms, which mainly ravaged eastern Africa countries has led to reduced agricultural productivity, massive job losses and weakened supply chains.The bank says sub-Saharan Africa is set to face its first recession in 25 years and will experience a negative economic growth of between 2.1 and 5.1 percent this year while agricultural productivity will fall by between 2.6 to seven percent.Data from the Kenya National Bureau of Statistics (KNBS) shows more than 1.7 million Kenyans lost their jobs between April and June at the onset of the pandemic.Small and medium-sized businesses, which account for a majority of total jobs in the market, have appealed to the government to be advanced with financing to reopen their businesses.Â 